Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Everingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire): habitational name from Everingham (East Yorkshire), named in Old English <i>Yferingaham</i> ‘homestead (<i>hām</i>) of the people (<i>-inga-</i>) of <i>Eofor</i>’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":10,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":19,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Everingham I was born in 1205, in Everingham, Yorkshire, England, his father, Thomas de Everingham, was 67 and his mother, Ragenilda de Cordonville, was 25. He married Isabel De Birkin. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died on 1 June 1246, in Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1205–1 June 1246":"1205–1. juuni 1246","1205–1246":"1205–1246","1209–1252":"1209–1252","1231–1280":"1231–1280","1233–Male":"1233–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1138–1205":"1138–1205","1180–1205":"1180–1205","1231":"1231","1252":"1252","1280":"1280","1180":"1180","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1138":"1138","1235":"1235","1 June 1246":"1. juuni 1246","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1233":"1233","Abt 1231":"umbes 1231","1199":"1199","1209":"1209","Everingham, Yorkshire, England":"Everingham, Yorkshire, England","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1205–1 June 1246":"1205–1. kesäkuuta 1246","1205–1246":"1205–1246","1209–1252":"1209–1252","1231–1280":"1231–1280","1233–Male":"1233–Kuollut","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1138–1205":"1138–1205","1180–1205":"1180–1205","1231":"1231","1252":"1252","1280":"1280","1180":"1180","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1138":"1138","1235":"1235","1 June 1246":"1. kesäkuuta 1246","1224":"1224","1246":"124